         <div>
            <head>29.10.1882 Sonntag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49069">Hamburg</placeName> October 29. 1882</p>
            <p> Really my diary is getting more of a Sunday chronicle than anything else, as I never
               have time to write except on Sundays. This afternoon I have been watching the
               children of the &#x201e;Waisenhaus&#x201c; dancing about on their lawn; but it is raining now so
               they have gone in. I do not know how it is but every day makes my antipathy to
                  <persName key="1157">Martin</persName> get greater. I am really getting not to be
               able to bear him: he seems to me to be a molycoddle, and a nervous, fawning
               half-proud boy and perfectly crackt. And I can not combat this antipathy. I wonder
               why it is? I this week again sent an article on the daily life in german schools to
               the <name type="periodical" key="70792">S. Georges Gazette</name>. I think it the
               best article I have ever written and certainly is the one I have taken most trouble
               about. The last one was dreadfully bad and I wonder <persName key="667">M<hi rend="ul.2">
                     <hi rend="sup">r</hi>
                  </hi> Kynnersley</persName> took it. <persName key="856">Aunt Lulu</persName>
               fetched me at two and we called upon <persName key="1159">M<hi rend="ul.2">
                     <hi rend="sup">ad.</hi>
                  </hi> Dellenburger</persName> and <persName key="4319">aunt
                  Auffm&#x2019;ordt</persName>
               <note type="reg">
                  <persName key="4319">Augusta</persName>
               </note> who was, in spite of her eighty five years very lively
               and pleasant. At 4.30 we went to the v. Sternfels&#x2019;es<note type="reg">
                  <persName key="72109">Manuela</persName> und <persName key="3730">Walter</persName>
               </note>
               who are very nice people. After dinner some more people came and those I remarked
               most were two fat, jolly, rosy girls who were very simple. We played Stop and one of
               the girls always lost although she had the best cards because she could not
               understand the game. But we amused ourselves very well playing and all kinds of
               things.</p>
         </div>
